    <exercise>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          While working on <xref text='title' ref="act-four-fours"/>, students solved the following expression in these four ways.
          
            <md>
              <mrow> \amp 4 + 4 / \sqrt{4} \times \sqrt{4} \amp \amp 4 + 4 / \sqrt{4} \times \sqrt{4} \amp \amp 4 + 4 / \sqrt{4} \times \sqrt{4} \amp \amp 4 + 4 / \sqrt{4} \times \sqrt{4}</mrow>
              <mrow> \amp = 4 + 4 / 2 \times 2 \amp \amp = 4 + 4 / 2 \times 2 \amp \amp = 4 + 4 / 2 \times 2 \amp \amp = 4 + 4 / 2 \times 2</mrow>
              <mrow> \amp = 4 + 4 / 4 \amp \amp = 8 / 4 \amp \amp = 4 + 2 \times 2 \amp \amp = 4 + 2 \times 2</mrow>
              <mrow> \amp = 4 + 1 \amp \amp = 2 \amp \amp = 4 + 4 \amp \amp = 6 \times 2</mrow>
              <mrow> \amp = 5 \amp \amp \amp \amp = 8 \amp \amp = 12</mrow>
            </md>
            
          
        </p>
      </introduction>

      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Only one solution can be correct. Which one is it? How do you know?
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>

      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            For the solutions above that are incorrect, identify the error(s) the student made.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>

      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            As you work on <xref text='title' ref="act-four-fours"/> check the expressions you find to make sure they work for the numbers you think they do. 
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Solve each of the following. Show how you know your work is correct.
        </p>
      </introduction>

      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Insert parentheses so this equation is true: <m>4 + 4 \div .4 \div \sqrt{4} = 7</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Insert parentheses so this equation is true: <m>\sqrt{4}^ \sqrt{4} + \sqrt{4} / 4 = 4</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Revisit <xref ref="exer-14-2a"/>. With no parentheses in the left side of the equation, what would the simplification of the expression be? Write the expression and show the simplification.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Look back at your work on the Four Fours Problem. Indicate where you used the mathematical properties and operations listed:
          <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
              Order of Operations
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Additive identity (adding zero, <m>4 +(4 - 4) = 4 + 0 = 4</m>; <m>\frac{4}{4}+(4-4)=1+0=1)</m>)
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              	Multiplicative identity (multiplying by <m>1= \frac{4}{4}=\frac{4}{\sqrt4\sqrt4}</m> )
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Fractions as divison, <m>\frac{44}{4} = 11</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Square root: <m>\sqrt{4} = 2</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Exponentiation: <m>4^{\sqrt4}=4^2=4 \cdot 4=16</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Factorials: <m>4! = 4 \cdot 3 \cdot 2 \cdot 1 = 24</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Concatenation: 44, 444
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Decimals: <m>4.4, .4, . \overline{4} = .4444444</m> <ellipsis/>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
